So, will `gmax` be the only thing that changes in segments, can other parameters not change? I think technically other parameters can also change: https://docs.neuroml.org/Userdocs/Schemas/Cells.html?highlight=inhomo#variableparameter ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 24, 14, 46, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sanjayankur31', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 953959935, 'comment_body': 'But how do we run it for hand written neuron files? (I don't like this average metric!)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 25, 15, 44, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sanjayankur31', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 955145066, 'comment_body': 'If we pass two sections as args to the function, then it will be an issue. If we are restricting the fucntion to only a section then we can go ahead with ave_all_segs. And if we plan to go with passing multiple sections as args then we should output `ave_all_sections` and [changing this line](https://github.com/NeuroML/pyNeuroML/blob/e019841058e38c59ad4388cc0afd4d72ef6213e5/pyneuroml/neuron/__init__.py#L455) with `numSecPresent += sec.nseg + 1` will solve it? ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 25, 15, 52, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'shayanshafquat', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 955156929, 'comment_body': 'Yeh, but not exactly. When we use the segments to get values, we're taking values from the centre of each segment to add up. When we take it only from the section (and not each segment), it only gives the value of the first segment: https://neuronsimulator.github.io/nrn/python/programming/mechstan.html?highlight=mechanismstandard#MechanismStandard._in So this average metric isn't a good one in general. If we do sections, then what it's actually saying is "average over all first segments (of all sections)", which isn't good for non-homogenous mechs either. A better way of calculating this would be over all segments for each section, and reporting that value for each section individually. But, would that be any more useful than the weak metric we have now?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 25, 16, 1, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sanjayankur31', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 955157932, 'comment_body': "Check my comment below---if it's showing one value, that implies that values on all segments are the same. @pgleeson I tried adding the dendritic current to other segments on the tuft and recorded from the same but wasn't lucky to replicate the same results with two spikes for the case (e). The rest of the plots look similar to the paper and the changes are good to be merged.

If we get this merged soon, I will be able to include the links of some of my work in the GSoC directory as well.
